    <node id="No, Opperly is not suggesting that the Thinkers could tempt or persuade Farquar to alter his scientific goals. Instead, he is implying that Farquar may be vulnerable to violence and using his position as a scientist to seize power for himself, rather than being &quot;bought off&quot; or having his aims changed by the Thinkers. Opperly believes that new ideas are not useful in bargaining for power, only established facts or lies are. He also thinks that Farquar wants to &quot;tease the animals&quot; and provoke the Thinkers for some personal reason. Overall, Opperly is cautioning against the use of violence and suggesting that the world needs magicians, or those who tell people what they wish were true, rather than scientists who tell people the truth." />
