    <node id="1. The Thinkers' power is primarily based on perception and manipulation rather than concrete achievements or facts. They have gained influence through means such as lucky guesses, faith-healing, and exploiting people's desire for mental comfort. Their perceived successes, like supposedly influencing the Soviet withdrawal from Iraq and Iran, are often based on false beliefs or misconceptions.&#10;2. The Thinkers' power is vulnerable because it is not founded on substantial accomplishments or truths. Opperly likens their influence to a cardboard fort, suggesting that they can be easily toppled once people recognize their flimsy foundation. Farquar also acknowledges the precariousness of their power, pointing out that a few well-placed pushes could expose their bluffs and guesswork.&#10;3. The Thinkers' vulnerability stems from the fact that they lack genuine achievements and instead rely on manipulation, deception, and luck. Once their facade is penetrated, their power will crumble, as people will no longer be swayed by their empty promises and false narratives." />
    <node id=". The erroneous belief that the Soviets pulled out of Iraq and Iran because of the Thinkers' Mind Bomb threat. A brain-machine that's just a cover for Jan Tregarron's guesswork. Oh, yes, and that hogwash of&#10;'Martian wisdom.' All of it mere bluff! A few pushes at the right times and points are all that are needed—and the Thinkers know it! I'll bet they're terrified already, and will be more so when they find that we're gunning for them. Eventually they'll be making overtures to us, turning to us for help. You wait and see.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;I am thinking again of Hitler,&quot; Opperly interposed quietly. &quot;On his first half dozen big steps, he had nothing but bluff. His generals were against him. They knew they were in a cardboard fort. Yet he won every battle, until the last. Moreover,&quot; he pressed on, cutting Farquar short, &quot;the power of the Thinkers isn't based on what they've got, but on what the world hasn't got—peace, honor, a good conscience....&quot;&#10; &#10; The front-door knocker clanked. Farquar answered it. A skinny old man" />
    <node id="Jorj Helmuth, the pilot, reaches orbit around Earth on the Mars rocket but his reaction is not one of excitement or curiosity about the view of Earth from space. Instead, he feels a sense of resignation as he knows he has two maddening months ahead of him. To spend his time, Jorj unstraps and interacts with his pet cat, Sappho, who enjoys the free fall in the cabin and plays with a string. Jorj grows bored and decides to study the wisdom he will discover on Mars, while Sappho curls up and goes to sleep in a spot she carefully selected off the floor. Sappho had adjusted well to zero gravity as she had experienced it before and loved it, bounding around the cabin in curves and gyrations. Jorj's interactions with his cat provide a brief respite from his more serious studies." />
    <node id="The rosy skin and strawberry bruises on the girl sleeping off a drunk in Old Washington suggest that despite the advanced technology and scientific achievements mentioned in the story, such as the nuclear heating unit and &quot;Maizie,&quot; the society still faces significant social issues. The fact that the girl is drunk and half-naked in a public place indicates a lack of strict law enforcement or a high level of acceptance for such behavior, which might be attributed to a permissive culture.&#10;&#10;At the same time, the story mentions &quot;America of the New Blue Laws,&quot; which implies some degree of moral conservatism and regulation. This inconsistency highlights the complex nature of American society at the end of the Twentieth Century in the story, where advanced technology coexists with persistent social problems and a mix of moral values.&#10;&#10;The contrasting effects of the rosy skin on various landmarks and people further illustrate this complexity. The color pink symbolizes warmth, love, and good health when it graces the white walls of Colonial dwellings or the face of an elderly physicist. However, it takes on a more ominous tone when associated with atomic bombs and their aftermath. These contrasts reflect the dual nature of America in the story, where both progress and destruction are present.&#10;&#10;In summary, the rosy skin and strawberry bruises on the girl suggest that despite the advanced technology and scientific achievements, American society still faces social issues like alcohol abuse and permissiveness, revealing a complex and inconsistent moral landscape at the end of the Twentieth Century in the story." />
    <node id=" rosy skin and strawberry bruises on the naked shoulders of a girl sleeping off a drunk on the furry and radiantly heated floor of a nearby roof garden. They struck green magic from the glassy blot that was Old Washington. Twelve hours before, they had revealed things as eerily beautiful, and as ravaged, in Asia and Russia. They pinked the white walls of the Colonial dwelling of Morton Opperly near the Institute for Advanced Studies; upstairs they slanted impartially across the Pharoahlike and open-eyed face of the elderly physicist and the ugly, sleep-surly one of young Willard Farquar in the next room. And in nearby New Washington they made of the spire of the Thinkers' Foundation a blue and optimistic glory that outshone White House, Jr.&#10; &#10; It was America approaching the end of the Twentieth Century. America of juke-box burlesque and your local radiation hospital. America of the mask-fad for women and Mystic Christianity. America of the off-the-bosom dress and the New Blue Laws. America of the Endless War and the loyalty detector. America of marvelous Maizie and the monthly rocket to Mars. America of the Thinkers and (a few remembered" />
