    <edge source=" above the ionosphere, the Mars rocket cut off its fuel and slumped gratefully into an orbit that would carry it effortlessly around the world at that altitude. The pilot unstrapped himself and stretched, but he didn't look out the viewport at the dried-mud disc that was Earth, cloaked in its haze of blue sky. He knew he had two maddening months ahead of him in which to do little more than that. Instead, he unstrapped Sappho.&#10; &#10; Used to free fall from two previous experiences, and loving it, the fluffy little cat was soon bounding about the cabin in curves and gyrations that would have made her the envy of all back-alley and parlor felines on the planet below. A miracle cat in the dream world of free fall. For a long time she played with a string that the man would toss out lazily. Sometimes she caught the string on the fly, sometimes she swam for it frantically.&#10; &#10; After a while the man grew bored with the game. He unlocked a drawer and began to study the details of the wisdom he would discover on Mars this trip—priceless spiritual insights that would be balm to war-battered mankind.&#10; &#10; The cat" target="Jorj Helmuth, the pilot, reaches orbit around Earth on the Mars rocket but his reaction is not one of excitement or curiosity about the view of Earth from space. Instead, he feels a sense of resignation as he knows he has two maddening months ahead of him. To spend his time, Jorj unstraps and interacts with his pet cat, Sappho, who enjoys the free fall in the cabin and plays with a string. Jorj grows bored and decides to study the wisdom he will discover on Mars, while Sappho curls up and goes to sleep in a spot she carefully selected off the floor. Sappho had adjusted well to zero gravity as she had experienced it before and loved it, bounding around the cabin in curves and gyrations. Jorj's interactions with his cat provide a brief respite from his more serious studies.">
