    <edge source="1. Relativism of moral values: In the world depicted in the story, traditional moral values seem to have eroded significantly. The actions and behaviors that were once considered unacceptable or immoral are now commonplace and accepted by society. This relativistic approach to morality raises questions about the very concept of objective moral values and suggests that they may be subject to change based on societal norms and circumstances.&#10;2. Power dynamics: In this world, power has become a driving force in shaping individual and collective actions. The Thinkers, representing a group with significant influence and resources, attempt to manipulate Farquar and Opperly by offering them positions of power and control. This portrayal highlights the potential dangers and ethical dilemmas that arise when power becomes the primary motivator in a value-less society.&#10;3. Role of violence: The story also touches upon the theme of violence, as Farquar is shown to have a proclivity for it. In a world without moral values, violence may become an increasingly common means of resolving conflicts and asserting dominance. This can lead to a cycle of escalating violence, further eroding any remaining sense of morality in society.&#10;4. The role of magicians vs. scientists: Opperly's argument that the world needs &quot;magicians&quot; rather than scientists suggests that people are more inclined to believe what they want to hear rather than facing uncomfortable truths. In a value-less society, this tendency may be exacerbated, as individuals seek comfort and easy answers in the face of uncertainty and instability.&#10;5. Nihilism: The story can be interpreted as an exploration of nihilism, where life lacks inherent meaning or purpose. With traditional moral values eroded, society appears to be aimless, without a clear sense of direction or shared goals. This raises questions about the importance of having a moral framework and the consequences of its absence.&#10;6. The dangers of power: The story underscores the potential dangers of unchecked power and the importance of safeguarding against it through checks and balances, as well as an adherence to moral values. In a world without morality, those with power may be tempted to act in their own self-interest, leading to exploitation and abuse.&#10;7. The potential for change: Despite the bleak portrayal of society in the story, it also highlights the possibility for change through new ideas and the courage to challenge the status quo. While Farquar's initial reaction is to confront the Thinkers with violence, Opperly cautions against this approach and encourages him to consider alternative strategies that may be more effective in bringing about meaningful change." target="Appointment in Tomorrow&#10; &#10; &#10; BY FRITZ LEIBER&#10; &#10; Illustrated by ED ALEXANDER&#10; &#10; [Transcriber's Note: This etext was produced from Galaxy Science Fiction July 1951. Extensive research did not uncover any evidence that the U.S. copyright on this publication was renewed.]&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10;&#10; Is it possible to have a world without moral values? Or does lack of morality become a moral value, also?&#10; &#10; &#10; &#10; The first angry rays of the sun—which, startlingly enough, still rose in the east at 24 hour intervals—pierced the lacy tops of Atlantic combers and touched thousands of sleeping Americans with unconscious fear, because of their unpleasant similarity to the rays from World War III's atomic bombs.&#10; &#10; They turned to blood the witch-circle of rusty steel skeletons around Inferno in Manhattan. Without comment, they pointed a cosmic finger at the tarnished brass plaque commemorating the martyrdom of the Three Physicists after the dropping of the Hell Bomb. They tenderly touched the rosy skin and strawberry bruises on the naked shoulders of a girl sleeping off a drunk on the furry and radiantly heated floor of a nearby roof garden. They">
