    <edge source=" machine with a million times as many synapses as the human brain, the machine that remembered by cutting delicate notches in the rims of molecules (instead of kindergarten paper-punching or the Coney Island shimmying of columns of mercury). This was the machine that had given instructions on building the last three-quarters of itself. This was the goal, perhaps, toward which fallible human reasoning and biased human judgment and feeble human ambition had evolved.&#10;  This was the machine that really thought—a million-plus!&#10; &#10; &#10; This was the machine that the timid cyberneticists and stuffy professional scientists had said could not be built. Yet this was the machine that the Thinkers, with characteristic Yankee push, had built. And nicknamed, with characteristic Yankee irreverence and girl-fondness, &quot;Maizie.&quot;&#10; &#10; Gazing up at it, the President of the United States felt a chord plucked within him that hadn't been sounded for decades, the dark and shivery organ chord of his Baptist childhood. Here, in a strange sense, although his reason rejected it, he felt he stood face to face with the living God: infinitely stern with the sternness of reality, yet infinitely just. No t" target="The rosy skin and strawberry bruises on the girl sleeping off a drunk in Old Washington suggest that despite the advanced technology and scientific achievements mentioned in the story, such as the nuclear heating unit and &quot;Maizie,&quot; the society still faces significant social issues. The fact that the girl is drunk and half-naked in a public place indicates a lack of strict law enforcement or a high level of acceptance for such behavior, which might be attributed to a permissive culture.&#10;&#10;At the same time, the story mentions &quot;America of the New Blue Laws,&quot; which implies some degree of moral conservatism and regulation. This inconsistency highlights the complex nature of American society at the end of the Twentieth Century in the story, where advanced technology coexists with persistent social problems and a mix of moral values.&#10;&#10;The contrasting effects of the rosy skin on various landmarks and people further illustrate this complexity. The color pink symbolizes warmth, love, and good health when it graces the white walls of Colonial dwellings or the face of an elderly physicist. However, it takes on a more ominous tone when associated with atomic bombs and their aftermath. These contrasts reflect the dual nature of America in the story, where both progress and destruction are present.&#10;&#10;In summary, the rosy skin and strawberry bruises on the girl suggest that despite the advanced technology and scientific achievements, American society still faces social issues like alcohol abuse and permissiveness, revealing a complex and inconsistent moral landscape at the end of the Twentieth Century in the story.">
